# CloudHub
This proof of concept demonstrates the retrieval of AWS billing info via API access and email parsing.

# AWS

## A. API 
https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/aws/new-programmatic-access-to-aws-billing-data/

According to [1](http://docs.aws.amazon.com/awsaccountbilling/latest/aboutv2/detailed-billing-reports.html)
During the current billing period (monthly), AWS generates *estimated* billing reports. 
The billing reports are not bills, but *estimates* of costs and charges for AWS usage. 
Only the monthly invoice you receive each month contains your *actual* charges.

## B. Email
The application uses the following Gmail search filter to identify monthly invoice emails from AWS:
```
from:aws-receivables-support@email.amazon.com from:aws-receivables@amazon.com
```

README.md – this document

# 2. Application Setup

The two maven apps were built using

- *.Java 8
- *.Maven 3
- *.AWS Java SDK 1.10
- *.Google Java Client SDK 1.20
- *.Log4j 1.2

You need to modify the following properties to match your environment:

| **Property Name** | File property is stored | Example Setting |

| data\_folder | /direct-api-access/pom.xml | C:\Work\CloudHub\direct-api-access\test\_files |
| time\_period | /direct-api-access/pom.xml | 2016-01 |
| bucket\_name\_aws | /direct-api-access/pom.xml | cloudhub-aws-demo |
|   |   |   |
| gmail\_data\_folder | /mailbox-search-and-parse/pom.xml | .gmail/credentials |
| time\_period | /mailbox-search-and-parse/pom.xml | 2016-01 |
| gmail\_user | /mailbox-search-and-parse/pom.xml | me |

# 4. Build Scripts Setup

Project 2 depends on project 1 so you need to compile and install project 1 before compiling/installing project 2 in maven.

## 4.1. AWS Setup
Before running any of the samples, please put your AWS credentials in the following location:
```
~/.aws/credentials on Linux, OS X or unix
C:\Users\USERNAME\.aws\credentials on Windows
```

The `credentials` file should contain the access key and secret as follows:
```
[default]
aws_access_key_id = your_access_key_id
aws_secret_access_key = your_secret_access_key
```

Alternatively, you could set them as environment variables.
on Linux, OS X or unix:
```
export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=your_access_key_id
export AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=your_secret_access_key
```
on Windows:
```
set AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=your_access_key_id
set AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=your_secret_access_key
```

## 4.2. Project 1
```
cd direct-api-access
mvn compile install
```

## 4.3. Project 2
```
cd mailbox-search-and-parse
mvn compile
```
